#MEM id=references source=/root/yvon/agent-department/COO/diana/skills/marketplace/lean-startup/references/build-measure-learn.md
M|references|The Build-Measure-Learn feedback loop is the core operating system of the Lean Startup. It transforms uncertainty into validated learning through rapid experimentation. The key insight most teams miss
M|references|Every loop iteration begins by asking: "What do we need to learn?" This reversal prevents the most common startup failure: building something nobody asked for.
M|references|| Step | Question | Output |
M|references||------|----------|--------|
M|references|| 1. Learn | What assumption must we validate? | Clear hypothesis |
M|references|| 2. Measure | What metric proves or disproves it? | Success/failure criteria |
M|references|| 3. Build | What is the minimum we must build to get that metric? | MVP specification |
M|references|**Learn goal:** Do freelance designers need automated invoicing?
M|references|**Measure plan:** Track sign-up conversion from landing page. Success = 5% conversion from targeted traffic (200 visitors minimum).
M|references|**Build plan:** Single landing page with value proposition, feature mockups, and email capture form. No actual product needed.
M|references|Once planned in reverse, execution runs forward:
M|references|Build the minimum artifact needed to run the experiment. This is not about building a product; it is about building a learning vehicle.
M|references|**Build phase checklist:**
M|references|- [ ] Hypothesis is written and visible to the team
M|references|- [ ] Success/failure criteria are defined before building
M|references|- [ ] The artifact is the smallest thing that can gen the needed data
M|references|- [ ] Time-box is set (typically 1-2 weeks for the build phase)
M|references|- [ ] No features are included that do not directly serve the hypothesis
M|references|Collect quantitative and qualitative data from real customer behavior.
M|references|**Measure phase checklist:**
M|references|- [ ] Instrumentation is in place before launch
M|references|- [ ] Baseline metrics are recorded
M|references|- [ ] Data collection method can distinguish signal from noise
M|references|- [ ] Sample size is sufficient for the dec being made
M|references|- [ ] Qualitative feedback channels are open (interviews, support, observation)
M|references|Analyze data, draw conclusions, and decide next action.
M|references|**Learn phase checklist:**
M|references|- [ ] Data is rv against pre-set criteria (not post-hoc rationalization)
M|references|- [ ] Team discusses what surprised them
M|references|- [ ] dec is made: persevere, pivot, or run another experiment
M|references|- [ ] Learnings are documented for organizational mem
M|references|- [ ] Next loop is planned based on this loop's output
M|references|The total time through one complete loop is your fundamental unit of progress. Reducing loop time is the single highest-leverage activity for a startup.
M|references|| Component | Typical Range | World-Class |
M|references||-----------|--------------|-------------|
M|references|| Build | 1-4 weeks | 1-3 days |
M|references|| Measure | 1-2 weeks | 1-3 days |
M|references|| Learn | 1 week | 1 day |
M|references|| **Total** | **3-7 weeks** | **3-7 days** |
M|references|1. **Reduce build scope.** The number one time sink. Ask "can we test this with less?"
M|references|2. **Pre-instrument everything.** Set up anl, event tracking, and dashboards before the build starts.
M|references|3. **Automate dpl.** Continuous dpl eliminates manual release bottlenecks.
M|references|4. **Set dec meetings in advance.** Schedule the "learn" rv before the experiment starts.
M|references|5. **Use existing platforms.** Build on top of Shopify, WordPress, Zapier, or Airtable instead of custom code.
M|references|**Hypothesis:** Small mkt teams will pay $49/month for AI-generated soc media captions.
M|references|| Phase | Activity | Duration |
M|references||-------|----------|----------|
M|references|| Build | Landing page with pricing, feature list, and "Start Free Trial" button that captures email | 3 days |
M|references|| Measure | Drive 500 targeted visitors via LinkedIn ads. Track: page views, CTA clicks, email signups | 7 days |
M|references|| Learn | 8% email capture rate, 40 signups. Qualitative: 12 replied to follow-up email expressing interest. dec: build concierge MVP for top 10 signups. | 1 day |
M|references|**Hypothesis:** Parents of toddlers want a screen-time tracker that suggests offline activities.
M|references|| Phase | Activity | Duration |
M|references||-------|----------|----------|
M|references|| Build | Clickable Figma prototype with 5 screens. Recruit 15 parents from local playgroups. | 5 days |
M|references|| Measure | Run 15 usability sessions. Track: task completion, time on task, Net Promoter Score, willingness to pay. | 5 days |
M|references|| Learn | Parents loved the activity suggestions but did not care about tracking. Pivot hypothesis to focus on curated activity recommendations only. | 1 day |
M|references|**Hypothesis:** Homeowners will pay a premium for pre-vetted, same-day handyman service.
M|references|| Phase | Activity | Duration |
M|references||-------|----------|----------|
M|references|| Build | Google Form for service requests. Manually match requests to 3 pre-vetted handymen. Charge via Square invoices. | 2 days |
M|references|| Measure | Post in 5 neighborhood Facebook groups. Track: form submissions, completed jobs, repeat requests, NPS. | 14 days |
M|references|| Learn | 23 requests, 18 completed jobs, 4 repeat customers. Willingness to pay a 20% premium confirmed. Supply side is the bottleneck. Next loop: test handyman recruitment and retention. | 1 day |
M|references|**Hypothesis:** Home brewers want a connected thermometer that alerts them during fermentation.
M|references|| Phase | Activity | Duration |
M|references||-------|----------|----------|
M|references|| Build | 3D-printed case with off-the-shelf temperature sensor and Bluetooth module. Basic app showing real-time temperature. | 10 days |
M|references|| Measure | Provide 10 units to home brewing club members for 2 brew cycles. Track: usage frequency, alert engagement, unsolicited feedback. | 21 days |
M|references|| Learn | 8 of 10 used it for both cycles. Alert feature was the most valued. Form factor needs to be waterproof. dec: invest in waterproof design, start pre-order cg. | 2 days |
M|references|Use this template for every loop iteration:
M|references|```
M|references|EXPERIMENT CARD
M|references|===============
M|references|Date: _______________
M|references|Loop #: _______________
M|references|HYPOTHESIS
M|references|What we believe: _______________
M|references|For whom: _______________
M|references|Because: _______________
M|references|METRIC
M|references|Primary metric: _______________
M|references|Current baseline: _______________
M|references|Success threshold: _______________
M|references|Failure threshold: _______________
M|references|BUILD
M|references|What we will build/create: _______________
M|references|Maximum time to build: _______________
M|references|Resources needed: _______________
M|references|MEASURE
M|references|How we collect data: _______________
M|references|Sample size needed: _______________
M|references|Duration of data collection: _______________
M|references|LEARN (fill after experiment)
M|references|Result: _______________
M|references|What surprised us: _______________
M|references|dec: [ ] Persevere  [ ] Pivot  [ ] Run another experiment
M|references|Next hypothesis: _______________
M|references|```
M|references|**Symptom:** Team keeps building without measuring. "Just one more feature and then we will launch."
M|references|**Fix:** Enforce a maximum build time-box of 2 weeks. If you cannot test a hypothesis in 2 weeks of building, the hypothesis is too big. Break it down.
M|references|**Symptom:** Every loop "succeeds" because the team measures page views, downloads, or sign-ups without connecting to value creation.
M|references|**Fix:** Every experiment must have an actionable metric with a pre-set dec threshold. If the metric goes up but does not change your next action, it is vanity.
M|references|**Symptom:** The Learn phase stretches for weeks. Team debates data endlessly without deciding.
M|references|**Fix:** Schedule the dec meeting before the experiment starts. Use pre-set criteria. If the data is ambiguous, run the experiment again with a larger sample or clearer metric, but decide that within 
M|references|**Symptom:** Team interprets all data as supporting their original idea. Pivots never happen.
M|references|**Fix:** Assign a "devil's advocate" for every Learn ses. Write down what data would cause you to abandon the idea before you see the data. Have someone outside the team rv the results.
M|references|**Symptom:** Team runs one experiment, declares success, and shifts to full-scale dev.
M|references|**Fix:** A single experiment validates a single assumption. Most products have 5-15 critical assumptions. Plan a sequence of loops, each targeting a different assumption.
M|references|**Symptom:** The team runs experiments but cannot recall what they learned three months ago. Same hypotheses get retested.
M|references|**Fix:** Maintain an experiment log (spreadsheet or wiki). Every experiment card gets archived with results. rv the log at the start of each new loop.
M|references|Run multiple experiments simultaneously when they test independent assumptions. A team of 6 can often run 2-3 concurrent loops if the assumptions do not depend on each other.
M|references|**When to parallelize:**
M|references|- Assumptions are independent (result of one does not affect another)
M|references|- Team has bandwidth without ctx-switching overhead
M|references|- Each loop has a dedicated owner
M|references|**When not to parallelize:**
M|references|- Assumptions are sequential (must validate A before B makes sense)
M|references|- Team is small (fewer than 4 people)
M|references|- Results from one experiment change the design of another
M|references|Techniques to compress a loop into days instead of weeks:
M|references|| Technique | How It Works | Best For |
M|references||-----------|-------------|----------|
M|references|| Five-second tests | Show a design for 5 seconds, ask what it communicates | Value proposition clarity |
M|references|| Fake door tests | Add a button/link for an unbuilt feature, measure clicks | Feature demand validation |
M|references|| Concierge MVP | Deliver the service manually to 5-10 customers | Service-based hypotheses |
M|references|| Painted door with survey | After click, explain feature is coming and ask 3 questions | Qualitative + quantitative signal |
M|references|| Pre-sell | Charge money before the product exists | Willingness-to-pay validation |
M|references|Establish a regular cadence to build organizational muscle:
M|references|- **Weekly loops** for early-stage, pre-product-market-fit teams
M|references|- **Bi-weekly loops** for teams with an existing product testing new features
M|references|- **Monthly loops** for hardware or complex B2B products with longer sales cycles
M|references|The cadence creates accountability. Every loop has a start date and an end date. Missing the cadence is a signal that scope is too large or the team needs help.
M|references|| Level | Description | Loop Time | Characteristics |
M|references||-------|-------------|-----------|-----------------|
M|references|| 1 - Ad hoc | No formal process | 2-3 months | Experiments happen accidentally |
M|references|| 2 - Aware | Team understands the concept | 4-6 weeks | Experiments are planned but not systematic |
M|references|| 3 - Practicing | Regular loop cadence | 2-3 weeks | Hypotheses documented, decisions data-informed |
M|references|| 4 - Proficient | Parallel loops, pre-set criteria | 1-2 weeks | Team challenges its own assumptions proactively |
M|references|| 5 - Mastery | Loops are second nature | 3-7 days | Continuous experimentation culture, institutional learning |
M|references|Most teams start at Level 1 or 2. Reaching Level 3 is a significant milestone. Levels 4 and 5 typically require organizational support, tooling, and cultural commitment.